{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778985835148,"sessionID":"ses_1cc3d92a0ffept8cGnkQSmvhEo","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_JnCxyRfI7R8l24iHjKcI1n5b","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n+## Issue #32005 research summary\n+\n+Target term: `GO:0009095` aromatic amino acid biosynthetic process, prephenate pathway.\n+\n+Conclusion: the term represents a combined pathway for biosynthesis of both L-phenylalanine and L-tyrosine from prephenate, while GO already contains separate pathway terms for the two biologically meaningful outputs:\n+\n+- `GO:0009094` L-phenylalanine biosynthetic process\n+- `GO:0006571` L-tyrosine biosynthetic process\n+\n+The MetaCyc xref on `GO:0009095` is `MetaCyc:PWY-3481`, which is the superpathway joining those two branches rather than a single pathway term appropriate for GO.\n+\n+## Candidate replacement terms checked\n+\n+- `GO:0009094` has narrowMatch xrefs to `MetaCyc:PWY-3462` and relevant prephenate-pathway wording in synonyms.\n+- `GO:0006571` has narrowMatch xrefs to `MetaCyc:PWY-3461`.\n+\n+## Direct annotation impact\n+\n+`runoak -i amigo: associations GO:0009095` returned 7 direct annotations:\n+\n+- 3 experimental IDA annotations from PubMed articles\n+- 1 experimental IDA annotation from MTBBASE\n+- 1 ISS annotation from UniProt\n+- 2 IEA annotations from UniProt\n+\n+No external ontology usages were found beyond GO's own axioms and xref material.\n+\n+## PMID:21102469 \"Prephenate aminotransferase directs plant phenylalanine biosynthesis via arogenate\"\n+\n+PubMed metadata validated by direct lookup.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:21102469 \"Biochemical and genetic characterization of enzymes showed that PPA-AT directs carbon flux from prephenate toward arogenate, making the arogenate pathway predominant in plant phenylalanine biosynthesis.\"\n+    - Supports phenylalanine biosynthesis specifically.\n+    - Also mentions tyrosine biosyntheses in the abstract, but the specific directional conclusion quoted above is about phenylalanine flux.\n+\n+Recommendations:\n+\n+- `UniProtKB:E9L7A5` (Petunia `PPA-AT`): replace `GO:0009095` with `GO:0009094`.\n+- `AGI_LocusCode:AT2G22250` (Arabidopsis `PAT`) annotated by UniProt from this PMID: likely replace with `GO:0009094` if curators keep a BP annotation from this paper.\n+\n+## PMID:20883697 \"Identification of a plant gene encoding glutamate/aspartate-prephenate aminotransferase: the last homeless enzyme of aromatic amino acids biosynthesis\"\n+\n+PubMed metadata validated by direct lookup.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:20883697 \"In all organisms synthesising phenylalanine and/or tyrosine via arogenate, a prephenate aminotransferase is required for the transamination of prephenate into arogenate.\"\n+    - Supports the enzyme activity and its pathway placement at the prephenate-to-arogenate step.\n+    - Does not, from the abstract alone, cleanly justify simultaneous annotation to both the phenylalanine and tyrosine biosynthetic processes.\n+\n+Recommendations:\n+\n+- `AGI_LocusCode:AT2G22250` (TAIR annotation): review manually; likely removal or migration to a more specific process only if supported from full text.\n+\n+## PMID:18727669 \"A comparative biochemical and structural analysis of the intracellular chorismate mutase (Rv0948c) from Mycobacterium tuberculosis H(37)R(v) and the secreted chorismate mutase (y2828) from Yersinia pestis\"\n+\n+PubMed metadata validated by direct lookup.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:18727669 \"The Rv0948c gene from Mycobacterium tuberculosis H(37)R(v) encodes a 90 amino acid protein as the natural gene product with chorismate mutase (CM) activity.\"\n+    - This paper supports chorismate mutase activity, not the combined prephenate-pathway biosynthetic process.\n+\n+Recommendations:\n+\n+- `UniProtKB:P9WIC1` (`Rv0948c`): remove the `GO:0009095` annotation rather than migrate it to the phenylalanine or tyrosine pathway terms.\n+\n+## Automated references\n+\n+- `GO_REF:0000117` IEA annotations and `GO_REF:0000024` ISS annotation should be remapped or removed downstream once the obsolete term is processed in annotation pipelines.\n+\n+## Notes\n+\n+- `linkml-reference-validator cache reference PMID:...` hit PubMed rate limiting (`HTTP 429`) in this environment, so PubMed pages were checked directly with `webfetch` instead.\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA RESEARCH.md","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,70 @@\n+## Issue #32005 research summary\n+\n+Target term: `GO:0009095` aromatic amino acid biosynthetic process, prephenate pathway.\n+\n+Conclusion: the term represents a combined pathway for biosynthesis of both L-phenylalanine and L-tyrosine from prephenate, while GO already contains separate pathway terms for the two biologically meaningful outputs:\n+\n+- `GO:0009094` L-phenylalanine biosynthetic process\n+- `GO:0006571` L-tyrosine biosynthetic process\n+\n+The MetaCyc xref on `GO:0009095` is `MetaCyc:PWY-3481`, which is the superpathway joining those two branches rather than a single pathway term appropriate for GO.\n+\n+## Candidate replacement terms checked\n+\n+- `GO:0009094` has narrowMatch xrefs to `MetaCyc:PWY-3462` and relevant prephenate-pathway wording in synonyms.\n+- `GO:0006571` has narrowMatch xrefs to `MetaCyc:PWY-3461`.\n+\n+## Direct annotation impact\n+\n+`runoak -i amigo: associations GO:0009095` returned 7 direct annotations:\n+\n+- 3 experimental IDA annotations from PubMed articles\n+- 1 experimental IDA annotation from MTBBASE\n+- 1 ISS annotation from UniProt\n+- 2 IEA annotations from UniProt\n+\n+No external ontology usages were found beyond GO's own axioms and xref material.\n+\n+## PMID:21102469 \"Prephenate aminotransferase directs plant phenylalanine biosynthesis via arogenate\"\n+\n+PubMed metadata validated by direct lookup.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:21102469 \"Biochemical and genetic characterization of enzymes showed that PPA-AT directs carbon flux from prephenate toward arogenate, making the arogenate pathway predominant in plant phenylalanine biosynthesis.\"\n+    - Supports phenylalanine biosynthesis specifically.\n+    - Also mentions tyrosine biosyntheses in the abstract, but the specific directional conclusion quoted above is about phenylalanine flux.\n+\n+Recommendations:\n+\n+- `UniProtKB:E9L7A5` (Petunia `PPA-AT`): replace `GO:0009095` with `GO:0009094`.\n+- `AGI_LocusCode:AT2G22250` (Arabidopsis `PAT`) annotated by UniProt from this PMID: likely replace with `GO:0009094` if curators keep a BP annotation from this paper.\n+\n+## PMID:20883697 \"Identification of a plant gene encoding glutamate/aspartate-prephenate aminotransferase: the last homeless enzyme of aromatic amino acids biosynthesis\"\n+\n+PubMed metadata validated by direct lookup.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:20883697 \"In all organisms synthesising phenylalanine and/or tyrosine via arogenate, a prephenate aminotransferase is required for the transamination of prephenate into arogenate.\"\n+    - Supports the enzyme activity and its pathway placement at the prephenate-to-arogenate step.\n+    - Does not, from the abstract alone, cleanly justify simultaneous annotation to both the phenylalanine and tyrosine biosynthetic processes.\n+\n+Recommendations:\n+\n+- `AGI_LocusCode:AT2G22250` (TAIR annotation): review manually; likely removal or migration to a more specific process only if supported from full text.\n+\n+## PMID:18727669 \"A comparative biochemical and structural analysis of the intracellular chorismate mutase (Rv0948c) from Mycobacterium tuberculosis H(37)R(v) and the secreted chorismate mutase (y2828) from Yersinia pestis\"\n+\n+PubMed metadata validated by direct lookup.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:18727669 \"The Rv0948c gene from Mycobacterium tuberculosis H(37)R(v) encodes a 90 amino acid protein as the natural gene product with chorismate mutase (CM) activity.\"\n+    - This paper supports chorismate mutase activity, not the combined prephenate-pathway biosynthetic process.\n+\n+Recommendations:\n+\n+- `UniProtKB:P9WIC1` (`Rv0948c`): remove the `GO:0009095` annotation rather than migrate it to the phenylalanine or tyrosine pathway terms.\n+\n+## Automated references\n+\n+- `GO_REF:0000117` IEA annotations and `GO_REF:0000024` ISS annotation should be remapped or removed downstream once the obsolete term is processed in annotation pipelines.\n+\n+## Notes\n+\n+- `linkml-reference-validator cache reference PMID:...` hit PubMed rate limiting (`HTTP 429`) in this environment, so PubMed pages were checked directly with `webfetch` instead.\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md","relativePath":"RESEARCH.md","type":"add","patch":"Index: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,70 @@\n+## Issue #32005 research summary\n+\n+Target term: `GO:0009095` aromatic amino acid biosynthetic process, prephenate pathway.\n+\n+Conclusion: the term represents a combined pathway for biosynthesis of both L-phenylalanine and L-tyrosine from prephenate, while GO already contains separate pathway terms for the two biologically meaningful outputs:\n+\n+- `GO:0009094` L-phenylalanine biosynthetic process\n+- `GO:0006571` L-tyrosine biosynthetic process\n+\n+The MetaCyc xref on `GO:0009095` is `MetaCyc:PWY-3481`, which is the superpathway joining those two branches rather than a single pathway term appropriate for GO.\n+\n+## Candidate replacement terms checked\n+\n+- `GO:0009094` has narrowMatch xrefs to `MetaCyc:PWY-3462` and relevant prephenate-pathway wording in synonyms.\n+- `GO:0006571` has narrowMatch xrefs to `MetaCyc:PWY-3461`.\n+\n+## Direct annotation impact\n+\n+`runoak -i amigo: associations GO:0009095` returned 7 direct annotations:\n+\n+- 3 experimental IDA annotations from PubMed articles\n+- 1 experimental IDA annotation from MTBBASE\n+- 1 ISS annotation from UniProt\n+- 2 IEA annotations from UniProt\n+\n+No external ontology usages were found beyond GO's own axioms and xref material.\n+\n+## PMID:21102469 \"Prephenate aminotransferase directs plant phenylalanine biosynthesis via arogenate\"\n+\n+PubMed metadata validated by direct lookup.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:21102469 \"Biochemical and genetic characterization of enzymes showed that PPA-AT directs carbon flux from prephenate toward arogenate, making the arogenate pathway predominant in plant phenylalanine biosynthesis.\"\n+    - Supports phenylalanine biosynthesis specifically.\n+    - Also mentions tyrosine biosyntheses in the abstract, but the specific directional conclusion quoted above is about phenylalanine flux.\n+\n+Recommendations:\n+\n+- `UniProtKB:E9L7A5` (Petunia `PPA-AT`): replace `GO:0009095` with `GO:0009094`.\n+- `AGI_LocusCode:AT2G22250` (Arabidopsis `PAT`) annotated by UniProt from this PMID: likely replace with `GO:0009094` if curators keep a BP annotation from this paper.\n+\n+## PMID:20883697 \"Identification of a plant gene encoding glutamate/aspartate-prephenate aminotransferase: the last homeless enzyme of aromatic amino acids biosynthesis\"\n+\n+PubMed metadata validated by direct lookup.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:20883697 \"In all organisms synthesising phenylalanine and/or tyrosine via arogenate, a prephenate aminotransferase is required for the transamination of prephenate into arogenate.\"\n+    - Supports the enzyme activity and its pathway placement at the prephenate-to-arogenate step.\n+    - Does not, from the abstract alone, cleanly justify simultaneous annotation to both t